# Adaptive/Mobile UI Best Practices

## Viewport Configuration
- Always include a proper viewport meta tag in the layout to ensure mobile responsiveness:
  ```html
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, maximum-scale=1.0, user-scalable=0" />
  ```

## Container and Width Management
- Use responsive max-width constraints to prevent horizontal overflow:
  ```jsx
  <div className="max-w-[100vw] sm:max-w-screen-2xl">
  ```
- For nested content, calculate available space using viewport units:
  ```jsx
  <div className="max-w-[calc(100vw-8px)]">
  ```
- Apply `overflow-hidden` to parent containers and `overflow-x-auto` to scrollable content

## Text and Code Blocks
- Use `break-all` for long text on mobile, with normal breaks on larger screens:
  ```jsx
  <code className="break-all sm:break-normal">
  ```
- For code blocks, limit width based on available space and enable horizontal scrolling:
  ```jsx
  <pre className="overflow-x-auto max-w-[calc(100vw-3rem)]">
  ```

## Responsive Spacing
- Use smaller padding on mobile and larger on desktop:
  ```jsx
  <div className="p-2 sm:p-4">
  ```
- Remember that our pattern is `{property}-{small value} sm:{property}-{larger value}`
- Standard mobile padding is 1px-2px, desktop is 4px-6px

## Flex Direction
- Stack elements vertically on mobile, horizontally on desktop:
  ```jsx
  <div className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row">
  ```
- Adjust alignment accordingly:
  ```jsx
  <div className="items-start sm:items-center">
  ```

## Typography
- Use smaller text on mobile:
  ```jsx
  <p className="text-xs sm:text-sm">
  ```
  ```jsx
  <h1 className="text-xl sm:text-2xl">
  ```

## Testing
- Always test designs on mobile devices and browsers
- Pay special attention to horizontal overflow issues
- Check both portrait and landscape orientations
